**Nobody Sees Your Ad Anymore**

Back in the old days, advertising was simpler. A big company with a famous brand was just that: a big company with a famous brand. As long as you could delivered on your promise, all you had to do was put up eye-catching ads on radio, billboards, perhaps TV, and your local newspaper.

Times have changed. Drastically.

**Selling your product just isn’t enough anymore.**

As people have tried to stand out, they have gotten increasingly aggressive in offering insane discounts and outlandish bonuses, sometimes bordering on bait-and-switch tactics. This has worn people out. Big offers don’t attract us anymore because we have figured out they really are too good to be true. Or, they just simply aren’t special anymore.

Your great discount isn’t a big deal any more because it’s one of a thousand great discounts “for a limited time only.”

Markets and cultures constantly influence and change each other. This is truer today than ever before. Several generations of heavy advertising has worn consumers down so much so that we aren’t merely immune to it, we’re tired of it.

**The truth is, you can get your ads seen again\!**

In order to appeal to the majority of today’s consumers, you have to present yourself as relatable--normal. People are tired of being aggressively sold to. They want honesty, justice, connection, and ultimately, community.

Watch yourself when you listen to the next salesperson or read the next advertisement. You may catch yourself waiting for the salesman to reveal an absurdly low price or the preacher to call for an offering.

Many others are asking the same about you:

* Is this person just in it for himself?  
* Does he even care about my well-being?  
* If he came down off that stage, would he listen to me or understand me?  
* Would he at least try to understand how I think, what I care about, and what I truly need?   
* Could I get along with him and feel at ease? Or would he be full of himself and aloof?

These are the questions your audience is asking about you. How are you answering them? Are you setting them at ease? Are you communicating that you understand and care and genuinely want to help?
